      "solution": "import java.util.*\n\nfun main() {\n    val input = Scanner(System.`in`)\n    val valsA = input.nextLine().substring(2).chunkedSequence(2) { Integer.parseInt(it.toString(), 16)}\n    val valsB = input.nextLine().substring(2).chunkedSequence(2) { Integer.parseInt(it.toString(), 16)}\n\n    // simple check whether rounding was necessary 1 means rounding - remove from test cases\n    val roundings = valsA.zip(valsB).map { (it.first + it.second) % 2 }\n    System.err.println(roundings.toList())\n\n    val results = valsA.zip(valsB).map { (it.first + it.second) / 2 }\n    println(\"0x\" + results.joinToString(\"\") { it.toString(16).toUpperCase().padStart(2, '0') })\n}",
      "statement": "Given 2 hex colors (with {{0x}} prefixes) compute middle color and output it as hex string (also with {{0x}} prefix).\n\nTest cases won't require any rounding.\n\nColor is defined in RGB channel where first 2 hex digits represent RED, second 2 hex digits represent GREEN and third 2 characters represent BLUE color (1 Byte). Middle color is computed as average of each of RED, GREEN, BLUE channels separately.\n\nFor example RED channel of {{0xFFAABB}} is {{FF}} and RED channel of {{0xABCCEF}} is {{AB}} - result RED channel is computed as average of those values ({{FF}} and {{AB}}) which is {{D5}}.",
